.TH _PRINTF 3 "2025" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom formatted output to stdout
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a
.I format
string and writes it to
.BR stdout .
It mimics the behaviour of the standard
.BR printf (3)
function from the C library, but is implemented from scratch using only
.BR write (2)
and the
.B va_*
macros from
.BR <stdarg.h> .
.PP
The
.I format
string is composed of zero or more directives:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Ordinary characters (not
.BR % ),
which are copied unchanged to the output.
.IP \(bu 2
Conversion specifications, each beginning with the character
.B %
and ending with a
.IR "conversion specifier" .
.RE
.SS Conversion specifiers
The following conversion specifiers are supported:
.TP
.B c
The
.I int
argument is converted to an
.I unsigned char
and the resulting character is written.
.TP
.B s
The
.I "const char *"
argument is expected to be a pointer to a null-terminated string.
Characters from the string are written up to (but not including) the
terminating null byte.
If the pointer is
.BR NULL ,
the string
.B (null)
is written instead.
.TP
.B d ", " i
The
.I int
argument is converted to signed decimal notation.
.TP
.B %
A
.B %
character is written. No argument is consumed.
.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used
to end output to strings).
.PP
If the
.I format
string is
.B NULL
or ends with an incomplete conversion specification (a lone
.BR % ),
.B \-1
is returned.
.SH NOTES
The following features of the standard
.BR printf (3)
are
.B not
supported in this implementation:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Flag characters
.RB ( \- ", " + ", " 0 ", " ' ' ", " # )
.IP \(bu 2
Field width
.IP \(bu 2
Precision
.IP \(bu 2
Length modifiers
.RB ( l ", " h ", " ll ", " ...)
.IP \(bu 2
Conversion specifiers other than those listed above
.RE
.PP
An unknown conversion specifier (e.g.\&
.BR %z )
is written literally (the
.B %
and the unknown character are both output).
.SH EXAMPLES
Print a simple string:
.PP
.RS
.nf
_printf("Hello, World!\\n");
.fi
.RE
.PP
Print an integer and a string:
.PP
.RS
.nf
_printf("User %s has id %d\\n", "alice", 42);
.fi
.RE
.PP
Print a literal percent sign:
.PP
.RS
.nf
_printf("Completion: 100%%\\n");
.fi
.RE
.PP
Retrieve the return value:
.PP
.RS
.nf
int len = _printf("Hi\\n");
/* len == 3 */
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3),
.BR write (2),
.BR stdarg (3)
